                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 837.00/538.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.—Extracts.—Paraphrases.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Habana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-01-11">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 11, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The House yesterday passed a resolution accusing officers of the Army and of the
                    Rural Guard of pernicious political activity and participation in seditious
                    manifestations; calling for a statement from the President of steps against
                    them, and information as to whether he had dealt with Monteagudo<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d329fn1">The general commanding the Army; he had issued a general
                        order forbidding soldiers to take part in the veterans’ movement to form a
                        political party.</note> for violations of military law. The newspapers
                    regard the situation as critical.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Beaupré</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
